post_cb({"1651336": {"Id": "1651336", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>According to <a href=\"http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/bxss3ska(VS.80).aspx\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">MSDN</a>: C and C++ programs consist of one or more source files, each of which contains some of the text of the program. A source file, together with its include files (files that are included using the #include preprocessor directive) but not including sections of code removed by conditional-compilation directives such as #if, is called a \"translation unit.\"</p>\n", "LastActivityDate": "2009-10-30T17:49:13.837", "CommentCount": "0", "CreationDate": "2009-10-30T17:49:13.837", "ParentId": "1106149", "Score": "1", "OwnerUserId": "128314"}, "1106149": {"ViewCount": "43499", "Body": "<p>I am reading at the time the \"Effective C++\" written by Meyers\nand came across the term \"translation unit\".</p>\n<p>Could somebody please give me an explanation of:</p>\n<p>1) What exactly it is </p>\n<p>2) When should I consider using it when programming with C++ </p>\n<p>3) If it is related only to C++, or it can be used with other programming languages</p>\n<p>I might already use it without knowing the term....</p>\n", "AcceptedAnswerId": "1106167", "Title": "What is a \"translation unit\" in C++", "CreationDate": "2009-07-09T20:01:13.810", "Id": "1106149", "CommentCount": "0", "FavoriteCount": "78", "PostTypeId": "1", "LastEditDate": "2009-07-09T20:05:19.493", "LastEditorUserId": "87234", "LastActivityDate": "2016-09-27T05:23:08.143", "Score": "168", "OwnerUserId": "61315", "Tags": "<c++>", "AnswerCount": "11"}, "8088891": {"Id": "8088891", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>In addition to the ODR, the translation unit is important in the definition of unnamed namespaces, which replaces one of the old uses of \"static\".  </p>\n<p>I guess I still don't have enough points to add a comment under the top answer.  </p>\n", "LastActivityDate": "2011-11-11T02:10:45.307", "CommentCount": "0", "CreationDate": "2011-11-11T02:10:45.307", "ParentId": "1106149", "Score": "4", "OwnerUserId": "527973"}, "1106172": {"Id": "1106172", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>A hard question to answer definitively. The C++ standard states:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_1106149_1106172_0\">The   text   of   the   program   is  kept   in   units   called source   files  in   this   International  Standard.  A   source   file \n             together   with   all   the   headers   (17.4.1.2)   and   source   files   included   (16.2)   via   the \n  preprocessing   directive         #include, less any source lines skipped by any of the\n  conditional inclusion (16.1)\n  preprocessing direc- \n             tives, is called a translation unit.   [Note: a C++ \n  program need not all be translated at\n  the same time.   ]</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>So for most intents and purposes a translation unit is a single C++ source file and the header or other files it includes via the preprocessor #include mechanism.</p>\n<p>Regarding your other questions:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_1106149_1106172_1\">2) When should I consider using it\n  when programming with C++</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>You can't not consider it - translation units are the basis of a C++ program.</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_1106149_1106172_2\">3) If it is related only to C++, or it\n  can be used with other programming\n  languages</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Other languages have similar concepts, but their semantics will be subtly different. Most other languages don't use a preprocessor, for example.</p>\n", "LastEditorDisplayName": "anon", "OwnerDisplayName": "anon", "LastActivityDate": "2009-07-09T20:51:08.373", "Score": "22", "CreationDate": "2009-07-09T20:06:12.487", "ParentId": "1106149", "CommentCount": "3", "LastEditDate": "2009-07-09T20:51:08.373"}, "bq_ids": {"n4140": {"so_1106149_1106172_0": {"length": 31, "quality": 0.7380952380952381, "section_id": 5311}}, "n3337": {"so_1106149_1106172_0": {"length": 31, "quality": 0.7380952380952381, "section_id": 5108}}, "n4659": {"so_1106149_1106172_0": {"length": 30, "quality": 0.7142857142857143, "section_id": 6735}}}, "1106167": {"Id": "1106167", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>From <a href=\"http://www.efnetcpp.org/wiki/Translation_unit\" rel=\"noreferrer\">here</a>: (<a href=\"http://web.archive.org/web/20090427201018/http://efnetcpp.org/wiki/Translation_unit\" rel=\"noreferrer\">wayback machine link</a>)</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_1106149_1106167_0\">According to <a href=\"http://www.efnetcpp.org/wiki/ISO/IEC_14882\" rel=\"noreferrer\">standard C++</a> (<a href=\"http://web.archive.org/web/20070403232333/http://www.efnetcpp.org/wiki/ISO/IEC_14882\" rel=\"noreferrer\">wayback machine link</a>) : \n  A translation unit is the basic unit\n  of compilation in C++. It consists of\n  the contents of a single source file,\n  plus the contents of any header files\n  directly or indirectly included by it,\n  minus those lines that were ignored\n  using conditional preprocessing\n  statements.</p>\n<p id=\"so_1106149_1106167_1\">A single translation unit can be\n  compiled into an object file, library,\n  or executable program.</p>\n<p id=\"so_1106149_1106167_2\">The notion of a translation unit is\n  most often mentioned in the contexts\n  of the One Definition Rule, and\n  templates.</p>\n</blockquote>\n", "LastEditorUserId": "73826", "LastActivityDate": "2016-09-27T05:23:08.143", "Score": "197", "CreationDate": "2009-07-09T20:05:34.970", "ParentId": "1106149", "CommentCount": "0", "OwnerUserId": "73826", "LastEditDate": "2016-09-27T05:23:08.143"}, "1106170": {"Id": "1106170", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>Every cpp/c (implementation) file will be converted into a translation unit (ie.,object file (.obj)) headers in the cpp file will be replaced with the actual text from the header files.</p>\n", "LastActivityDate": "2009-07-09T20:06:06.247", "CommentCount": "0", "CreationDate": "2009-07-09T20:06:06.247", "ParentId": "1106149", "Score": "0", "OwnerUserId": "22076"}, "1106162": {"Id": "1106162", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>A translation unit is for all intents and purposes a file (.c/.cpp), <em>after</em> it's finished including all of the header files.</p>\n<p><a href=\"http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/bxss3ska%28VS.80%29.aspx\" rel=\"noreferrer\">http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/bxss3ska%28VS.80%29.aspx</a></p>\n", "LastActivityDate": "2009-07-09T20:03:24.380", "CommentCount": "4", "CreationDate": "2009-07-09T20:03:24.380", "ParentId": "1106149", "Score": "51", "OwnerUserId": "5728"}, "29120698": {"Id": "29120698", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>C and C++ programs consist of one or more source files, each of which contains some of the text of the program. A source file, together with its include files (files that are included using the #include preprocessor directive) but not including sections of code removed by conditional-compilation directives such as #if, is called a \"translation unit.\"</p>\n", "LastActivityDate": "2015-03-18T11:21:39.983", "CommentCount": "0", "CreationDate": "2015-03-18T11:21:39.983", "ParentId": "1106149", "Score": "1", "OwnerUserId": "4684978"}, "17933243": {"Id": "17933243", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>In my view, a \"translation unit\" is typically a single \"post-preprocessing\" source file. You can get more details on this MSDN page. <a href=\"http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/bxss3ska(v=vs.80).aspx\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/bxss3ska(v=vs.80).aspx</a></p>\n", "LastActivityDate": "2013-07-29T20:08:34.657", "CommentCount": "0", "CreationDate": "2013-07-29T20:08:34.657", "ParentId": "1106149", "Score": "0", "OwnerUserId": "2631678"}, "1106164": {"Id": "1106164", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>The book makes it clear enough.  When Meyers referes to a \"translation Unit\", he means a source code file.</p>\n", "LastActivityDate": "2009-07-09T20:03:48.327", "CommentCount": "6", "CreationDate": "2009-07-09T20:03:48.327", "ParentId": "1106149", "Score": "7", "OwnerUserId": "1053"}, "1106169": {"Id": "1106169", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>A translation unit is code that is passed to the compiler proper.  This typically means the output from running the preprocessor on the .c file.</p>\n", "LastActivityDate": "2009-07-09T20:06:05.857", "CommentCount": "0", "CreationDate": "2009-07-09T20:06:05.857", "ParentId": "1106149", "Score": "2", "OwnerUserId": "78720"}, "1106271": {"Id": "1106271", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>As others have said, a translation unit is basically the contents of a source file after preprocessing.  It's the topmost production in the language grammar; you would only need to worry about it if you were writing a C or C++ compiler.  </p>\n", "LastActivityDate": "2009-07-09T20:30:03.830", "CommentCount": "1", "CreationDate": "2009-07-09T20:30:03.830", "ParentId": "1106149", "Score": "0", "OwnerUserId": "134554"}});